🧱 EPIC — Platform Architecture Evolution
1. Context / Problem (Before)

Before this initiative, the platform had several structural limitations that impacted scalability, maintainability, and operational efficiency:

Network coupling across clusters (L3 overlap)
→ All clusters shared the same IP range, limiting scalability and isolating cluster growth
Manual / fragmented cluster provisioning
→ No standardized or automated way to create clusters across Proxmox/Talos environments
Lack of unified service exposure strategy
→ Ingress and routing patterns were inconsistent and not designed for multi-cluster scenarios
Limited service discovery approach
→ No clear, scalable model for cross-cluster communication or dynamic routing
Operational overhead
→ High manual effort required for setup, redeployment, and changes
2. Constraints

The solution had to operate within the following constraints:

Use of Talos OS (immutable Kubernetes)
Deployment on Proxmox-based infrastructure
Networking limitations within existing environment
No full service mesh adoption (by design / constraints)
Security and isolation requirements between clusters
Need for compatibility with existing tooling (e.g., Rancher, GitOps workflows)
3. Approach / Architecture (Why this design)

To address these challenges, a new platform architecture was designed with focus on automation, scalability, and clear separation of concerns.

Key design decisions:

Decoupled cluster networking
Each cluster operates with independent network ranges
Enables horizontal scalability and avoids IP conflicts
Automated cluster provisioning
Terraform integrated with NetBox and Proxmox
Dynamic IP allocation and infrastructure consistency
Standardized routing layer
Introduction of a unified ingress strategy (e.g., Traefik / Envoy-based)
Support for TLS passthrough and flexible service exposure
Service discovery model (non-mesh)
gRPC/xDS-inspired approach for dynamic configuration
Avoids complexity of full service mesh while retaining flexibility
GitOps-based deployment strategy
Integration with ArgoCD
Enables reproducible deployments (blue/green, potential canary)
Platform abstraction
Reduce infrastructure complexity for consumers (developers / teams)
Provide consistent interfaces for cluster usage
4. What Changed (Impact of the Architecture)
From manual → automated provisioning
From network-coupled → scalable multi-cluster design
From ad-hoc routing → standardized ingress model
From limited visibility → structured platform architecture
Reduced operational complexity and improved deployment consistency
5. Outcome / Value
Improved scalability of cluster environments
Increased platform reliability and consistency
Reduced manual effort and operational overhead
Enabled future extensibility (multi-cluster, advanced routing, etc.)
Established a foundation for platform standardization
